tr:personRole></gtr:personRoles><gtr:project url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=ES%2FE010350%2F1"><gtr:id>D6D24F82-A36F-4E7F-AF92-E71C0B838239</gtr:id><gtr:title>Conditional Cash Transfers, Risk, Savings and Investments</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Fellowship</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>ES/E010350/1</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>Poor people in rural communities are exposed to a broad array of shocks that might imply important income losses. To cope with risk, households adopt sophisticated mechanisms: precautionary savings, informal credit or mutual insurance. However, perfect risk sharing and smooth-consumption are doubtfully attained and households remain vulnerable. In parallel, conditional cash transfer programs (CCTs) have become increasingly popular in the developing world as a mechanism to fight poverty. CCTs provide money to poor families contingent upon investments in human capital. Although they have been proved successful in increasing schooling, consumption and health care; little is known about their role as a safety net. Within this proposal,&amp;nbsp;it is&amp;nbsp;argued that CCTs can also serve as a tool for households to smooth consumption, increase self-insurance and reduce risk vulnerability through -&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p> 
&lt;ul> 
 &lt;li>A&amp;nbsp;direct increase in unearned income, &lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>An increase in household production income through investment, &lt;/li> 
 &lt;li>A&amp;nbsp;reduction in risk exposure. &lt;/li>
&lt;/ul> 
&lt;p>The research intends to extend Rosenzweig and Wolpin?s (1993) model of agricultural investment under uncertainty and test its predictions using household panel data on risk, assets and consumption collected as part of the evaluations of two major CCTs currently operating in Latin America: Mexico?s Oportunidades and Colombia?s Familias en Acci&amp;oacute;n. &lt;br />&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-12-31</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2007-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>149314</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">ES/E010350/1</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>EBACD6D4-D1E5-4970-8BEC-7F4568EB26BA</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Development studies</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>7D5D2DB2-0A64-42AF-A644-5F541B832A29</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Economics</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>64564C94-AC7F-4056-903D-0AED107A359E</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Education</gtr:text></gtr:researchSubject><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>12179D88-04B3-47E9-89E1-B5EE8F895227</gtr:id><gtr:percentage>0</gtr:percentage><gtr:text>Social Policy</gtr:text></gtr: